SIMPLE: right
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Right
<hw>Right</hw> <pr>(r⟦imac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>right</ets>, <ets>riht</ets>, AS. <ets>riht</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>regt</ets>, OS. & OHG. <ets>reht</ets>, G. <ets>recht</ets>, Dan.
<ets>ret</ets>, Sw. r⟦aum⟧tt, Icel. <ets>rettr</ets>, Goth.
<ets>ra⟦iacute⟧hts</ets>, L. <ets>rectus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>regere</ets> to guide, rule; cf. Skr. <ets>⟦rsdot⟧ju</ets>
straight, right. ⟦root⟧115. Cf. <er>Adroit</er>,<er>Alert</er>,
<er>Correct</er>, <er>Dress</er>, <er>Regular</er>, <er>Rector</er>,
<er>Recto</er>, <er>Rectum</er>, <er>Regent</er>, <er>Region</er>,
<er>Realm</er>, <er>Rich</er>, <er>Royal</er>, <er>Rule</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Straight; direct; not crooked; <as>as, a <ex>right</ex>
line</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Right</xex> as any line.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Upright; erect from a base; having an upright axis;
not oblique; <as>as, <ex>right</ex> ascension; a <ex>right</ex> pyramid
or cone.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Conformed to the constitution of man and the will of
God, or to justice and equity; not deviating from the true and just;
according with truth and duty; just; true.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That which is conformable to the Supreme Rule is absolutely
<qex>right</qex>, and is called <qex>right</qex> simply without relation
to a special end.</q> <rj><qau>Whately.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fit; suitable; proper; correct; becoming; <as>as,
the <ex>right</ex> man in the <ex>right</ex> place; the <ex>right</ex>
way from London to Oxford.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Characterized by reality or genuineness; real;
actual; not spurious.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧His <xex>right</xex> wife.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In this battle, . . . the Britons never more plainly manifested
themselves to be <qex>right</qex> barbarians.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>According with truth; passing a true judgment;
conforming to fact or intent; not mistaken or wrong; not erroneous;
correct; <as>as, this is the <ex>right</ex> faith</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You are <qex>right</qex>, Justice, and you weigh this well.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If there be no prospect beyond the grave, the inference is . . .
<qex>right</qex>, ⟦ldquo⟧Let us eat and drink, for to-morrow we
die.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Most favorable or convenient; fortunate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lady has been disappointed on the <qex>right</qex> side.</q>
<rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to that side of the body in man on
which the muscular action is usually stronger than on the other side; --
opposed to <xex>left</xex> when used in reference to a part of the body;
<as>as, the <ex>right</ex> side, hand, arm</as>. Also applied to the
corresponding side of the lower animals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Became the sovereign's favorite, his <qex>right</qex> hand.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In designating the banks of a river, <xex>right</xex>
and <xex>left</xex> are used always with reference to the position of
one who is facing in the direction of the current's flow.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Well placed, disposed, or adjusted; orderly; well
regulated; correctly done.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Designed to be placed or worn outward; <as>as, the
<ex>right</ex> side of a piece of cloth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>At right angles</b></col>, <cd>so as to form a right
angle or right angles, as when one line crosses another
perpendicularly.</cd> -- <col><b>Right and left</b></col>, <cd>in both
or all directions.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>Right and left
coupling</b></col> <fld>(Pipe fitting)</fld>, <cd>a coupling the
opposite ends of which are tapped for a right-handed screw and a
left-handed screw, respectivelly.</cd> -- <col><b>Right angle</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The angle formed by one line meeting another
perpendicularly, as the angles <xex>ABD</xex>, <xex>DBC</xex>.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Spherics)</fld> <cd>A spherical angle included
between the axes of two great circles whose planes are perpendicular to
each other.</cd> -- <col><b>Right ascension</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Ascension</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Right Center</b></col>
<fld>(Politics)</fld>, <cd>those members belonging to the Center in a
legislative assembly who have sympathies with the Right on political
questions. See <er>Center</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 5.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Right cone</b></col>, <col><b>Right cylinder</b></col>,
<col><b>Right prism</b></col>, <col><b>Right pyramid</b></col></mcol>
<fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>a cone, cylinder, prism, or pyramid, the axis of
which is perpendicular to the base.</cd> -- <col><b>Right
line</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Line</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Right
sailing</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>sailing on one of the four
cardinal points, so as to alter a ship's latitude or its longitude, but
not both.</cd> <au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au> -- <col><b>Right
sphere</b></col> <fld>(Astron. & Geol.)</fld>, <cd>a sphere in such a
position that the equator cuts the horizon at right angles; in spherical
projections, that position of the sphere in which the primitive plane
coincides with the plane of the equator.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Right</xex> is used elliptically for <xex>it is
right</xex>, <xex>what you say is right</xex>,
<xex>true</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧<qex>Right</qex>,⟦rdquo⟧ cries his lordship.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Straight; direct; perpendicular; upright; lawful;
rightful; true; correct; just; equitable; proper; suitable;
becoming.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Right</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Right
<hw>Right</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In a right
manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In a right or straight line; directly; hence;
straightway; immediately; next; <as>as, he stood <ex>right</ex> before
me; it went <ex>right</ex> to the mark; he came <ex>right</ex> out; he
followed <ex>right</ex> after the guide.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unto Dian's temple goeth she <qex>right</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let thine eyes look <qex>right</qex> on.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. iv.
25.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Right</qex> across its track there lay,⟦br⟧
Down in the water, a long reef of gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Exactly; just.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Came he <qex>right</qex> now to sing a raven's note?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>According to the law or will of God; conforming to
the standard of truth and justice; righteously; <as>as, to live
<ex>right</ex>; to judge <ex>right</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>According to any rule of art; correctly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You with strict discipline instructed <qex>right</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>According to fact or truth; actually; truly; really;
correctly; exactly; <as>as, to tell a story <ex>right</ex></as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Right</xex> at mine own cost.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Right</qex> as it were a steed of Lumbardye.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His wounds so smarted that he slept <qex>right</qex> naught.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>In a great degree; very; wholly; unqualifiedly;
extremely; highly; <as>as, <ex>right</ex> humble; <ex>right</ex> noble;
<ex>right</ex> valiant</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧He was not <xex>right</xex>
fat⟦rdquo⟧. <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For which I should be <qex>right</qex> sorry.</q>
<rj><qau>Tyndale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[I] return those duties back as are <qex>right</qex> fit.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In this sense now chiefly prefixed to titles; as,
<xex>right</xex> honorable; <xex>right</xex> reverend.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Right honorable</b></col>, <cd>a title given in England
to peers and peeresses, to the eldest sons and all daughters of such
peers as have rank above viscounts, and to all privy councilors; also,
to certain civic officers, as the lord mayor of London, of York, and of
Dublin.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1242 --></p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Right</xex> is used in composition with other
adverbs, as up<xex>right</xex>, down<xex>right</xex>,
forth<xex>right</xex>, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Right along</b></col>, <cd>without cessation;
continuously; <as>as, to work <ex>right along</ex> for several
hours</as>.</cd> <mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark> -- <mcol><col><b>Right
away</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Right off</b></col></mcol>, <cd>at
once; straightway; without delay.</cd> <mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧We will . . . shut ourselves up in the office and do the work
<xex>right off</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>D. Webster.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Right</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Right
<hw>Right</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>right</ets>.
See <er>Right</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is
right or correct.</def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The straight
course; adherence to duty; obedience to lawful authority, divine or
human; freedom from guilt, -- the opposite of moral
<xex>wrong</xex>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A true statement; freedom from
error of falsehood; adherence to truth or fact.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seldom your opinions err;⟦br⟧
Your eyes are always in the <qex>right</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>A just judgment or action; that which is true or
proper; justice; uprightness; integrity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Long love to her has borne the faithful knight,⟦br⟧
And well deserved, had fortune done him <qex>right</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That to which one has a just claim.</def>
<specif>Specifically:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>That which one has a
natural claim to exact.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There are no <qex>rights</qex> whatever, without corresponding
duties.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>That which one has a legal or social claim to do or
to exact; legal power; authority; <as>as, a sheriff has a <ex>right</ex>
to arrest a criminal</as>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>That which justly
belongs to one; that which one has a claim to possess or own; the
interest or share which anyone has in a piece of property; title; claim;
interest; ownership.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Born free, he sought his <qex>right</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hast thou not <qex>right</qex> to all created things?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men have no <qex>right</qex> to what is not reasonable.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>Privilege or immunity granted by
authority.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The right side; the side opposite to the
left.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Led her to the Souldan's <qex>right</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>In some legislative bodies of Europe (as in France),
those members collectively who are conservatives or monarchists. See
<er>Center</er>, 5.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The outward or most finished surface, as of a piece
of cloth, a carpet, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>At all right</b></col>, <cd>at all points; in all
respects.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>Bill of
rights</b></col>, <cd>a list of rights; a paper containing a declaration
of rights, or the declaration itself. See under <er>Bill</er>.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>By right</b></col>, <col><b>By rights</b></col>,
<it>or</it> <col><b>By good rights</b></col></mcol>, <cd>rightly;
properly; correctly.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He should himself use it <qex>by right</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I should have been a woman <qex>by right</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>Divine right</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Divine right
of kings</b></col>, <cd>a name given to the patriarchal theory of
government, especially to the doctrine that no misconduct and no
dispossession can forfeit the right of a monarch or his heirs to the
throne, and to the obedience of the people.</cd> -- <col><b>To
rights</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>In a direct line; straight.</cd>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <au>Woodward.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>At once;
directly.</cd> <mark>[Obs. or Colloq.]</mark> <au>Swift.</au> --
<mcol><col><b>To set to rights</b></col>, <col><b>To put to
rights</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to put in good order; to adjust; to
regulate, as what is out of order.</cd> -- <col><b>Writ of
right</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a writ which lay to recover lands
in fee simple, unjustly withheld from the true owner.</cd>
<au>Blackstone.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Right</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Right
<hw>Right</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Righted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Righting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>rihtan</ets>. See
<er>Right</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring or
restore to the proper or natural position; to set upright; to make right
or straight (that which has been wrong or crooked); to
correct.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To do justice to; to relieve from wrong; to restore
rights to; to assert or regain the rights of; <as>as, to <ex>right the
oppressed</ex>; <ex>to right</ex> one's self</as>; also, to
vindicate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So just is God, to <qex>right</qex> the innocent.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All experience hath shown that mankind are more disposed to suffer
while evils are sufferable, than to <qex>right</qex> themselves by
abolishing the forms to which they are accustomed.</q>
<rj><qau>Jefferson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To right a vessel</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
restore her to an upright position after careening.</cd> -- <col><b>To
right the helm</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to place it in line
with the keel.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Right</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Right
<hw>Right</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To recover the proper
or natural condition or position; to become upright.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>Hence, to regain an upright
position, as a ship or boat, after careening.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Right-about</ent>⟦br⟧
